 of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone whose dwelling was by a river or lake, Middle English <i>atte water</i> ‘at the water’.","History: This surname was established from an early date in New England. David Atwater was one of the group of settlers who founded the New Haven colony in 1638."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Atwater was born in 1365, in Kent, England as the son of William Atwater. He married Joan Williams in 1389, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1415, in Lenham, Kent, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1365–1415":"1365–1415","1369–1434":"1369–1434","1390–1481":"1390–1481","1390–1484":"1390–1484","1345–1395":"1345–139